			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> paper:</span><br><i>Semantics First! Rethinking the Language Design Process</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MartinErwig.html">Martin Erwig</a>, <a href="../profile/EricWalkingshaw.html">Eric Walkingshaw</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_14">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_14</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a language design methodology that starts from semantics and derives other aspects.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The ‘semantics first’ stance makes behavioral/executable semantics a primary design driver.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> The approach relies on formal semantic reasoning to guide language design decisions.
</li></ul></li></ul>
